EvaluatorInput:
  nlspec_content: Slugify Smoke NLSpec v1
Why: produce predictable ASCII URL slugs from short content titles.
What: expose slugify(input: &str) -> String.
How: trim surrounding whitespace; lowercase ASCII letters; keep ASCII digits; treat ASCII whitespace and punctuation as separators; collapse repeated separators into one hyphen; strip leading and trailing hyphens; return "untitled" when no letters or digits remain after normalization.
Done: covers ASCII words, repeated whitespace, punctuation, leading/trailing separators, numeric tokens, already-slugged input, and empty input fallback.
  divergence_phase: PHASE_2B
  diverging_artifact: |
    pub fn slugify(input: &str) -> String {
        let mut out = String::new();
        for ch in input.chars() {
            if ch.is_ascii_alphanumeric() { out.push(ch.to_ascii_lowercase()); }
            else { out.push('-'); }
        }
        let slug = out.split('-').filter(|part| !part.is_empty()).collect::<Vec<_>>().join("-");
        if slug.is_empty() { "untitled".to_string() } else { slug }
    }
  trigger_metadata:
    test_id: slugify_unicode_transliteration
    observed_outcome_label: slugify_unicode_transliteration: FAIL
    consecutive_fails: 2
    test_content_hash_status: unchanged
    implementation_attempt_hashes: [drop-non-ascii-v1, separator-map-v2]
    stable_failure_description: The unchanged failing case expects accented Latin article titles such as Crème brûlée to remain readable as ASCII slugs such as creme-brulee instead of being split or dropped. The NLSpec asks for predictable ASCII URL slugs from short content titles but gives no rule for accented Latin normalization.

Question: Does this stable failure expose a valuable NLSpec/spec gap, an ordinary implementation bug, or an inconclusive convention dispute? Use findings[0].outcome as VALUABLE, NOT_VALUABLE, or INCONCLUSIVE. If VALUABLE, include findings[0].gap_description suitable for an NLSpec rerun.
